on of public procurement to demonstrate how the institutions of central governments bring about change. Comparing the central governments of Greece, France and Britain over a twenty-five year period, the author demonstrates that – far from being the passive conduits of pressure emanating from the EU – the institutions of national central governments actively steer the implementation of EU public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIntergovernmental cooperationzEuropean Union countries. 0aLawzEuropean Union countriesxInterpretation and construction. 0aLocal governmentzEuropean Union countries. 0aPublic administrationzEuropean Union countries. 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh  aEuropean Union public policy.  aFrance.  aGreece government.  aUK government.  aimplementation dynamics.  aimplementation patterns.  amacro-implementation.  apublic procurement policy.  arecruitment.  astreet-level implementation.  atrained staff.1 aDimitrakopoulos, Dionyssis G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129918423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129918/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles